hands_on_practices.problem:
A clinical neurophysiology laboratory performs Single-Fiber Electromyography (SFEMG) on the extensor digitorum muscle to evaluate neuromuscular junction (NMJ) transmission in a patient with fatigable weakness. Single-Fiber Electromyography (SFEMG) records action potentials from two individual muscle fibers belonging to the same motor unit and, across repeated discharges, measures the interpotential interval between a reference fiber and a test fiber. In synaptic physiology, variability in quantal release and postsynaptic depolarization timing at the neuromuscular junction leads to fluctuations in the time from reference fiber activation to test fiber activation; this fluctuation is termed jitter. The laboratory adopts the operational definition that jitter is the root-mean-square of the consecutive interpotential interval variation across repeated discharges.

Starting from the core facts that (i) the neuromuscular junction introduces stochastic variability in transmission time and (ii) consecutive discharges of the same motor unit generate a sequence of interpotential intervals whose differences quantify transmission instability, derive the appropriate mathematical computation to obtain the jitter as a root-mean-square measure of consecutive interpotential interval variation. Then, using the following sequence of interpotential intervals measured over $N$ consecutive discharges,
$$
I_{1} = 512\,\mu\text{s},\;
I_{2} = 560\,\mu\text{s},\;
I_{3} = 502\,\mu\text{s},\;
I_{4} = 570\,\mu\text{s},\;
I_{5} = 515\,\mu\text{s},\;
I_{6} = 590\,\mu\text{s},\;
I_{7} = 530\,\mu\text{s},\;
I_{8} = 600\,\mu\text{s},\;
I_{9} = 520\,\mu\text{s},\;
I_{10} = 605\,\mu\text{s},\;
I_{11} = 535\,\mu\text{s},
$$
compute the jitter by the root-mean-square of the consecutive interpotential interval variation and provide the numerical value.

Finally, based on the magnitude of the computed jitter relative to typical healthy adult laboratory reference limits for SFEMG jitter in extensor digitorum (commonly on the order of tens of microseconds), explain why increased jitter is expected in disorders of neuromuscular transmission and what pathophysiologic mechanisms at the neuromuscular junction produce such increases.

Round your final numerical answer to three significant figures and express it in microseconds ($\mu\text{s}$). The final answer must be a single number.
